    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras are positioned for a high-ceiling offensive output today, anchored by **Trea Turner** (81.18) and **Kyle Schwarber** (77.08). Both are premium starts against Luis Severino, benefiting from a favorable wind projection that provides a +5% boost, pushing their daily efficiency scores into the elite tier. **Dillon Dingler** (63.90) and **Carson Benge** (62.91) also emerge as core plays; **Dillon Dingler** leverages a significant +14% dynamic platoon advantage against Jovani Mor\u00e1n, while **Carson Benge** benefits from a highly favorable park factor (+14%) in his matchup against Michael Lorenzen. Despite an elite xERA (2.81) from opposing pitcher Shohei Ohtani, **Yordan Alvarez** remains a locked-in starter with a 55.68 score, buoyed by his elite xwOBA (.428) which maintains his floor even against top-tier arms.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved keeping **Caleb Durbin** on the bench with a 48.70 score. While **Caleb Durbin** is a priority add for our SB-starved build, the optimizer favored **Chase Meidroth** (62.45) due to the latter\u2019s favorable matchup against Sam Aldegheri and a higher projected spot in the lineup. We are closely monitoring the status of **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (57.25); despite a -15% drag from his platoon split against Andrew Abbott, his +4% SB potential remains critical given our league's scarcity of speed, making him a high-leverage watch despite the risk.\n\nRisk management remains a theme, as we are navigating \"Lineup Pending\" status across the board. We are particularly cautious regarding the wind-in factor affecting **Gary Sanchez** (51.54), which dragged his efficiency score down by 5% and makes him a marginal play compared to our stronger middle-infield options. We continue to manage our bench depth effectively, keeping **Hyeseong Kim** (45.63) as an emergency pivot, while continuing to monitor the recovery timelines for **Christian Yelich** and the development of **Zac Veen** in the 